Japanese, Australian Stock Futures Gain on Earnings, Weaker Yen

-- B y   N o r i e   K u b o y a m a   a n d   T o s h i r o   H a s e g a w a
-- 
2011-05-10T23:16:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-10/japanese-australia-stock-futures-increase-on-earnings-outlook-weaker-yen.html
Japanese and Australian stock futures
gained as a better outlook for company earnings boosts
confidence about the recovery in the global economy.  American depositary receipts of  Toyota Motor Corp. (7203) , the
world’s largest carmaker, rose 0.9 percent from the closing
share price in Tokyo. Those of  Sony Corp. (6758) , Japan’s No. 1
electronics exporter, gained 1.3 percent after the yen weakened,
boosting the earnings outlook for exporters. ADRs of  BHP
Billiton Ltd. (BHP) , Australia’s No. 1 oil producer and the world’s
biggest mining company, increased 0.7 percent.  “The global economy is on a track to recovery,” said
 Hiroichi Nishi , an equities manager in Tokyo at SMBC Nikko
Securities Inc. “The yen’s appreciation, which was weighing on
the exporters and the related stocks, is taking a pause. That
will likely boost the stock market.”  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
June closed at 9,905 in Chicago yesterday, compared with 9,820
in Osaka, Japan. The futures were bid in the pre-market at 9,900
in Osaka, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Futures on Australia’s
S&P/ASX 200 Index gained 1 percent today. New Zealand’s NZX 50
Index increased 0.3 percent in Wellington.  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index rose 0.1 percent
today. In New York, the index advanced 0.8 percent to 1,357.16
yesterday, rising for a third day as higher-than-estimated
profit forecasts and  Microsoft Corp. (MSFT) ’s purchase of Skype
Technologies SA bolstered optimism that earnings and takeovers
will keep fueling the rally.  Microsoft Purchase  Dean Foods Co. (DF) , the largest U.S. milk processor, raised its
full-year earnings forecast and posted first-quarter profit that
exceeded analysts’ estimates.  Microsoft agreed to buy Skype Technologies SA for $8.5
billion, using a growing cash pile to gain the world’s most
popular Web-calling service and help it catch up in online and
mobile advertising, according to a statement yesterday.  The yen slid versus its major counterparts, dropping
against the euro for the first time in six days, as gains in
stocks and commodities damped demand for safer assets. The euro
rose versus the dollar after a spokesman for German Chancellor
 Angela Merkel  said restructuring of Greece’s debt isn’t being
considered.  The yen depreciated to as low as 116.72 against the euro
today in  Tokyo , snapping a five-day gain. That compares with 115
at the close of  stock trading  yesterday. Against the dollar,
Japan’s currency weakened to 81.01 from 80.49. A weaker yen
boosts the value of overseas income at Japanese companies when
repatriated.  Crude Oil   Crude oil for June delivery rose 1.3 percent to $103.88 a
barrel yesterday in New York, the highest settlement since May 4.
The London Metal Exchange Index of six metals including copper
and aluminum advanced for a third day, rising 0.7 percent
yesterday.  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index rose 0.2 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with gains of 7.9 percent by the S&P
500 and 2.6 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index.  Stocks in the Asian benchmark are valued at 13.4 times
estimated earnings on average, compared with 13.7 times for the
S&P 500 and 11.4 times for the Stoxx 600.  Of the 448 companies in the MSCI index that have reported
results for the latest quarter, 172 have exceeded analysts’
estimates, while 173 have missed them, according to data
compiled by Bloomberg.  To contact the reporters on this story:
